<![CDATA[<a href="https://instagram.com/p/DIH_wnythft/">View on Instagram</a><p><img src="https://scontent-bos5-1.cdninstagram.com/v/t51.2885-15/488672265_17941950077988600_2042027057733061251_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_e35_p1080x1080_sh0.08_tt6&_nc_ht=scontent-bos5-1.cdninstagram.com&_nc_cat=100&_nc_oc=Q6cZ2QELoHZV6lTyV3YQ-ztclPUEIjFr0e2aY4f-OHAvjOfYmyt1ZS-0hugLwkPCosvZqyw&_nc_ohc=Dg_HAZB1NEgQ7kNvwHdpw1i&_nc_gid=aLXOln3jw9jpVDi0SKETOA&edm=AGenrX8BAAAA&ccb=7-5&oh=00_AfKZ7C7Wp94I_0wseVAm4ScajCXFYxwCvL8sd1IvN5l1GQ&oe=682AA4C4&_nc_sid=ed990e" /><br>But for real… Hell or High Water, born out of necessity after Hurricane Helene ravaged Black Mountain (and the rest of WNC), is a testament to strength, resilience, and the power of community. The food is locally sourced and focused on creating a connection between the land, the farmers, and the people they serve. The meal was incredible, legitimately, and we felt the love the whole way through. @hellorhighwaterbmt Go show Black Mountain businesses some sweet, sweet lovin’ ♥️ #community #blackmountain #asheville #restaurant #foodies]]>
